Primitive (Basic) Data Types in C 

Primitive data types are the fundamental data types provided by C. They store single values and form the building blocks for other data types. 

List of Primitive Data Types 

int 

float 

double 

char 

void 

 

1. int (Integer) 

Used to store whole numbers 

Size: 4 bytes (depends on compiler) 

Can store positive and negative values 

Example: 

#include <stdio.h> 
 
int main() { 
   int number = 25; 
   printf("Number = %d", number); 
   return 0; 
} 
 

 

2. float 

Used to store decimal values 

Size: 4 bytes 

Precision: up to 6 decimal places 

Example: 

#include <stdio.h> 
 
int main() { 
   float salary = 25000.50; 
   printf("Salary = %f", salary); 
   return 0; 
} 
 

 

3. double 

Used to store decimal values with higher precision 

Size: 8 bytes 

Precision: up to 15 decimal places 

Example: 

#include <stdio.h> 
 
int main() { 
   double pi = 3.14159265359; 
   printf("Value of pi = %lf", pi); 
   return 0; 
} 
 

 

4. char 

Used to store a single character 

Size: 1 byte 

Stored internally as ASCII value 

Example: 

#include <stdio.h> 
 
int main() { 
   char grade = 'A'; 
   printf("Grade = %c", grade); 
   return 0; 
} 
 

 

5. void 

Represents no value 

Commonly used with functions that do not return anything 

Example: 

#include <stdio.h> 
 
void display() { 
   printf("Welcome to C Programming"); 
} 
 
int main() { 
   display(); 
   return 0; 
} 
 

 

