Variants of int in C 

short int 

unsigned short int 

int 

unsigned int 

long int 

unsigned long int 

long long int 

unsigned long long int 

Single Example Program (All int Variants) 

#include <stdio.h> 
 
int main() { 
 
   short int a = -32768; 
   unsigned short int b = 65535; 
 
   int c = -100000; 
   unsigned int d = 100000; 
 
   long int e = -123456789; 
   unsigned long int f = 123456789; 
 
   long long int g = -1234567890123; 
   unsigned long long int h = 1234567890123; 
 
   printf("short int a = %hd\n", a); 
   printf("unsigned short int b = %hu\n\n", b); 
 
   printf("int c = %d\n", c); 
   printf("unsigned int d = %u\n\n", d); 
 
   printf("long int e = %ld\n", e); 
   printf("unsigned long int f = %lu\n\n", f); 
 
   printf("long long int g = %lld\n", g); 
   printf("unsigned long long int h = %llu\n", h); 
 
   return 0; 
} 
 

 

Key Notes (Important for Exams & Interviews) 

signed is default for int 

unsigned stores only positive values 

long long int is used for very large numbers 

Format specifiers must match the data type 

 

